---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout 
  title="TurboQuant — 6× KV Cache Compression via Near-Optimal Vector Quantization"
  description="How Google Research's TurboQuant achieves 6× KV cache memory reduction with 3-bit precision. Interactive visualization of vector quantization, codebook design, and distortion-rate tradeoffs."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: "Home", href: "/" },
    { label: "LLM", href: "/llm/" },
    { label: "TurboQuant", href: "/llm/turboquant/" }
  ]}
>
  <div class="viz-container">
    <header class="viz-header">
      <h1>⚡ TurboQuant</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">6× less KV cache memory via near-optimal vector quantization — Google Research, 2025</p>
    </header>

    <!-- Why It Matters -->
    <section class="overview-section">
      <div class="overview-card">
        <p>
          The KV cache is the memory bottleneck of LLM inference. A single Llama 70B session with 128K context needs 
          <strong>~40 GB</strong> just for cached keys and values. TurboQuant compresses these vectors from 16-bit down to 
          <strong>~2.7 bits per dimension</strong> — a <strong>6× reduction</strong> — while preserving the geometric structure 
          (inner products, distances) that attention depends on. Unlike scalar quantization (round each number independently), 
          TurboQuant uses <strong>vector quantization</strong>: it encodes entire vectors as indices into a learned codebook, 
          exploiting correlations between dimensions that scalar methods waste.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The Core Problem -->
    <section class="panel">
      <h2>🧠 The Core Problem: KV Cache Eats Memory</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">During generation, every token's Key and Value vectors are cached. Memory grows linearly with sequence length.</p>
      <div class="kv-calc">
        <div class="calc-controls">
          <div class="ctrl-group">
            <label>Sequence Length: <strong id="seqLenLabel">32,768</strong></label>
            <input type="range" id="seqLenSlider" min="1024" max="131072" value="32768" step="1024">
          </div>
          <div class="ctrl-group">
            <label>Model</label>
            <select id="modelSelect">
              <option value="llama7b" selected>Llama 7B (32L × 32H × 128d)</option>
              <option value="llama70b">Llama 70B (80L × 64H × 128d)</option>
              <option value="llama405b">Llama 405B (126L × 128H × 128d)</option>
            </select>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="mem-comparison" id="memBars"></div>
        <div class="mem-stats">
          <div class="stat-card fp16">
            <span class="stat-label">FP16 (baseline)</span>
            <span class="stat-value" id="memFp16">—</span>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-card int8">
            <span class="stat-label">INT8 (2× compression)</span>
            <span class="stat-value" id="memInt8">—</span>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-card int4">
            <span class="stat-label">INT4 (4× compression)</span>
            <span class="stat-value" id="memInt4">—</span>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-card turbo">
            <span class="stat-label">TurboQuant (~6× compression)</span>
            <span class="stat-value" id="memTurbo">—</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Scalar vs Vector Quantization -->
    <section class="panel">
      <h2>🔢 Scalar vs Vector Quantization</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">
        Scalar quantization rounds each number independently. Vector quantization encodes the <em>whole vector</em> as an 
        index into a codebook — capturing correlations between dimensions. This is why vector methods can achieve lower 
        distortion at the same bit rate.
      </p>
      <div class="svq-demo">
        <div class="svq-side">
          <h4>Scalar Quantization</h4>
          <p class="svq-desc">Each dimension quantized independently → loses inter-dimension structure</p>
          <canvas id="scalarCanvas" width="360" height="360"></canvas>
          <div class="svq-stat">
            <span>Avg distortion: <strong id="scalarDist">—</strong></span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="svq-side">
          <h4>Vector Quantization</h4>
          <p class="svq-desc">Entire vector mapped to nearest codebook entry → preserves structure</p>
          <canvas id="vectorCanvas" width="360" height="360"></canvas>
          <div class="svq-stat">
            <span>Avg distortion: <strong id="vectorDist">—</strong></span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="svq-controls">
        <button class="action-btn" id="svqResample">🔄 New Vectors</button>
        <div class="ctrl-group inline">
          <label>Bits per vector: <strong id="bpvLabel">3</strong></label>
          <input type="range" id="bpvSlider" min="1" max="6" value="3">
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- How TurboQuant Works -->
    <section class="panel">
      <h2>⚙️ How TurboQuant Works</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Three key innovations that achieve near-optimal distortion rates.</p>

      <div class="steps-grid">
        <div class="step-card">
          <div class="step-num">1</div>
          <div class="step-body">
            <h4>Random Rotation (Data-Oblivious)</h4>
            <p>
              Apply a random orthogonal rotation to each KV vector. This spreads the information evenly across all dimensions, 
              making the vector more "quantization-friendly." Unlike methods like GPTQ or AWQ, TurboQuant doesn't need calibration 
              data — the rotation is <strong>data-oblivious</strong>, chosen without seeing any training examples.
            </p>
            <div class="formula">
              <code>v' = R · v</code> where R is a random orthogonal matrix
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <div class="step-num">2</div>
          <div class="step-body">
            <h4>Lattice-Based Codebook</h4>
            <p>
              Instead of learning a codebook from data (like k-means), TurboQuant uses a <strong>structured lattice</strong> — 
              a mathematically optimal arrangement of codewords in high-dimensional space. The lattice minimizes worst-case 
              distortion for any data distribution. Lookup is O(d) per vector (no nearest-neighbor search needed).
            </p>
            <div class="formula">
              <code>q(v') = argmin<sub>c ∈ Λ</sub> ‖v' - c‖²</code> — nearest lattice point
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <div class="step-num">3</div>
          <div class="step-body">
            <h4>Near-Optimal Distortion Rate</h4>
            <p>
              Shannon's rate-distortion theory gives a theoretical lower bound on how much you can compress before quality 
              degrades. TurboQuant achieves distortion within a <strong>constant factor</strong> of this theoretical minimum — 
              it's provably near-optimal. For b bits per dimension, MSE distortion ≈ <code>O(2<sup>-2b</sup>)</code>.
            </p>
            <div class="formula">
              <code>D(b) ≤ C · 2<sup>-2b</sup> · σ²</code> — matches Shannon's bound
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Inner Product Preservation -->
    <section class="panel">
      <h2>🎯 Why Inner Products Matter</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">
        Attention computes <code>softmax(Q · K<sup>T</sup>)</code>. The KV cache stores K and V. If quantization distorts the 
        inner products between Q and K, attention weights shift and output quality degrades. TurboQuant is specifically designed 
        to preserve inner product structure — not just individual values.
      </p>
      <div class="ip-demo">
        <canvas id="ipCanvas" width="700" height="280"></canvas>
        <div class="ip-controls">
          <button class="action-btn" id="ipResample">🔄 New Vectors</button>
          <div class="ip-legend">
            <span class="legend-item"><span class="legend-dot" style="background:#22c55e"></span> True inner products</span>
            <span class="legend-item"><span class="legend-dot" style="background:#f59e0b"></span> Scalar quantized</span>
            <span class="legend-item"><span class="legend-dot" style="background:#00d4ff"></span> Vector quantized (TurboQuant)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ip-stats">
          <div class="stat">
            <span class="stat-val" id="ipErrScalar">—</span>
            <span class="stat-label">Scalar IP Error</span>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <span class="stat-val" id="ipErrVector">—</span>
            <span class="stat-label">TurboQuant IP Error</span>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <span class="stat-val" id="ipImprove">—</span>
            <span class="stat-label">Improvement</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Distortion-Rate Curve -->
    <section class="panel">
      <h2>📉 Distortion-Rate Tradeoff</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">
        More bits = less distortion. TurboQuant's curve tracks close to the theoretical Shannon bound, 
        while scalar quantization plateaus early. At 3 bits, TurboQuant achieves what scalar methods need ~5 bits for.
      </p>
      <canvas id="drCanvas" width="700" height="350"></canvas>
      <div class="dr-annotations">
        <div class="dr-note sweet">
          <strong>Sweet spot:</strong> 2.7-3 bits per dimension → 6× compression vs FP16, 
          attention speedup ~8× on H100 (memory-bound → compute-bound transition)
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Speed Impact -->
    <section class="panel">
      <h2>🚀 Speed Impact on H100</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">
        Attention is memory-bandwidth-bound during decoding. Smaller KV cache = fewer bytes to load = faster attention. 
        At 3-bit KV cache, attention becomes <strong>compute-bound instead of memory-bound</strong>.
      </p>
      <div class="speed-bars">
        <div class="speed-row">
          <span class="speed-label">FP16 KV (baseline)</span>
          <div class="speed-bar-track">
            <div class="speed-bar-fill" style="width:100%; background:#64748b;">
              <span>1×</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="speed-row">
          <span class="speed-label">INT8 KV</span>
          <div class="speed-bar-track">
            <div class="speed-bar-fill" style="width:50%; background:#3b82f6;">
              <span>2×</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="speed-row">
          <span class="speed-label">INT4 KV</span>
          <div class="speed-bar-track">
            <div class="speed-bar-fill" style="width:25%; background:#f59e0b;">
              <span>4×</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="speed-row">
          <span class="speed-label">TurboQuant (~3-bit)</span>
          <div class="speed-bar-track">
            <div class="speed-bar-fill turbo-glow" style="width:12.5%; background:linear-gradient(90deg, #00d4ff, #22c55e);">
              <span>8×</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="speed-note">
        * Speedup is for the attention computation specifically. End-to-end inference speedup depends on how much time 
        is spent in attention vs FFN layers (typically 40-60% at long contexts).
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Comparison Table -->
    <section class="panel">
      <h2>📊 TurboQuant vs Other KV Cache Methods</h2>
      <div class="compare-table">
        <div class="ct-header">
          <span>Method</span><span>Type</span><span>Bits</span><span>Compression</span><span>Calibration</span><span>IP Preservation</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>Round-to-Nearest</span><span>Scalar</span><span>4-8</span><span>2-4×</span><span>None</span>
          <span class="quality ok">Medium</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>KIVI</span><span>Scalar</span><span>2-4</span><span>4-8×</span><span>Required</span>
          <span class="quality ok">Medium</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>QJL</span><span>Projection</span><span>1</span><span>16×</span><span>None</span>
          <span class="quality bad">Low</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>PolarQuant</span><span>Polar VQ</span><span>2-4</span><span>4-8×</span><span>None</span>
          <span class="quality good">High</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row highlight">
          <span><strong>TurboQuant</strong></span><span>Lattice VQ</span><span>~2.7</span><span><strong>~6×</strong></span><span>None</span>
          <span class="quality good"><strong>Near-optimal</strong></span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Hardware Implications -->
    <section class="panel">
      <h2>💰 What This Means for Hardware</h2>
      <div class="implications-grid">
        <div class="impl-card green">
          <h4>✅ Who Benefits</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Cloud providers</strong> — serve 6× more concurrent users per GPU</li>
            <li><strong>Long-context apps</strong> — 128K context fits where 21K used to</li>
            <li><strong>Edge inference</strong> — run bigger models on smaller devices</li>
            <li><strong>Batch inference</strong> — more requests in-flight simultaneously</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="impl-card red">
          <h4>⚠️ Who's Worried</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>HBM manufacturers</strong> — if you need 6× less memory, demand drops</li>
            <li><strong>Infra investors</strong> — $1T in AI datacenter debt meets falling memory needs</li>
            <li><strong>GPU vendors</strong> — selling points shift from memory capacity to compute</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="takeaway-card">
        <p>
          <strong>The bigger picture:</strong> TurboQuant is part of a wave of algorithmic efficiency improvements 
          (FlashAttention, PagedAttention, speculative decoding, MoE) that reduce the hardware needed per inference. 
          The question is whether these savings get spent on running bigger models and longer contexts — or actually 
          reduce hardware demand. History suggests the former (Jevons' paradox).
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Paper Reference -->
    <section class="panel ref-panel">
      <h2>📄 Paper</h2>
      <div class="ref-card">
        <p class="ref-title">TurboQuant: Online Vector Quantization with Near-optimal Distortion Rate</p>
        <p class="ref-authors">Amir Zandieh, Majid Daliri, Majid Hadian, Vahab Mirrokni — Google Research, April 2025</p>
        <p class="ref-links">
          <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.20268" target="_blank" rel="noopener">arXiv</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Related -->
    <section class="panel">
      <h2>🔗 Related Topics</h2>
      <div class="related-grid">
        <a href="/llm/kv-cache/" class="related-link">KV Cache & Inference →</a>
        <a href="/llm/quantization/" class="related-link">Model Quantization →</a>
        <a href="/llm/transformer/" class="related-link">Transformer Architecture →</a>
        <a href="/llm/gpu-memory/" class="related-link">GPU Memory Hierarchy →</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <style>
    .viz-container { max-width: 1100px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 1rem; }
    .viz-header { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .viz-header h1 { font-size: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .overview-card { background: #1e293b; border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; border-left: 4px solid #00d4ff; }
    .overview-card p { color: #cbd5e1; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0; }

    .panel { background: #0f172a; border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    h2 { color: #f1f5f9; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
    .section-desc { color: #94a3b8; margin-bottom: 1rem; line-height: 1.6; }
    .section-desc code { background: #1e293b; padding: 0.15rem 0.4rem; border-radius: 4px; color: #00d4ff; font-size: 0.9rem; }

    .ctrl-group { margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
    .ctrl-group label { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.85rem; display: block; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; }
    .ctrl-group input[type=range] { width: 100%; }
    .ctrl-group select { background: #1e293b; color: #f1f5f9; border: 1px solid #334155; border-radius: 6px; padding: 0.5rem; width: 100%; }
    .ctrl-group.inline { display: inline-block; min-width: 200px; margin-left: 1rem; vertical-align: middle; }

    /* KV Calc */
    .calc-controls { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; max-width: 600px; }
    .mem-comparison { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .mem-stats { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 0.8rem; }
    .stat-card { background: #1e293b; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.3rem; }
    .stat-card .stat-label { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.8rem; }
    .stat-card .stat-value { color: #f1f5f9; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; }
    .stat-card.turbo { border: 2px solid #00d4ff; }
    .stat-card.turbo .stat-value { color: #00d4ff; }

    /* SVQ Demo */
    .svq-demo { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .svq-side { text-align: center; }
    .svq-side h4 { color: #f1f5f9; margin: 0 0 0.3rem; }
    .svq-desc { color: #64748b; font-size: 0.8rem; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
    .svq-side canvas { background: #1e293b; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; max-width: 360px; }
    .svq-stat { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
    .svq-controls { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }

    .action-btn { padding: 0.6rem 1.2rem; border: none; border-radius: 8px; background: #3b82f6; color: white; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.85rem; }
    .action-btn:hover { background: #2563eb; }

    /* Steps */
    .steps-grid { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem; }
    .step-card { display: flex; gap: 1rem; background: #1e293b; border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.2rem; }
    .step-num { width: 40px; height: 40px; background: #00d4ff; border-radius: 50%; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 800; color: #0f172a; flex-shrink: 0; font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .step-body h4 { color: #f1f5f9; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
    .step-body p { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; }
    .formula { background: #0f172a; border-radius: 6px; padding: 0.6rem 0.8rem; margin-top: 0.8rem; font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.85rem; color: #22c55e; }
    .formula code { color: #22c55e; background: none; padding: 0; }

    /* IP Demo */
    .ip-demo canvas { background: #1e293b; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; max-width: 700px; }
    .ip-controls { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem; margin-top: 0.8rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
    .ip-legend { display: flex; gap: 1rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
    .legend-item { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.3rem; font-size: 0.8rem; color: #94a3b8; }
    .legend-dot { width: 10px; height: 10px; border-radius: 50%; }
    .ip-stats { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: 1rem; margin-top: 1rem; }
    .stat { text-align: center; }
    .stat .stat-val { display: block; font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 700; color: #f1f5f9; }
    .stat .stat-label { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.8rem; }

    /* DR Canvas */
    #drCanvas { background: #1e293b; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; max-width: 700px; }
    .dr-annotations { margin-top: 0.8rem; }
    .dr-note { padding: 0.8rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.5; }
    .dr-note.sweet { background: #00d4ff15; border: 1px solid #00d4ff40; color: #94a3b8; }
    .dr-note strong { color: #00d4ff; }

    /* Speed Bars */
    .speed-bars { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.6rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .speed-row { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem; }
    .speed-label { width: 160px; color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.85rem; flex-shrink: 0; text-align: right; }
    .speed-bar-track { flex: 1; background: #1e293b; border-radius: 8px; height: 36px; overflow: hidden; }
    .speed-bar-fill { height: 100%; border-radius: 8px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: flex-end; padding-right: 0.8rem; font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.9rem; color: white; min-width: 50px; transition: width 0.6s ease; }
    .turbo-glow { box-shadow: 0 0 16px rgba(0, 212, 255, 0.4); }
    .speed-note { color: #64748b; font-size: 0.8rem; font-style: italic; }

    /* Comparison Table */
    .compare-table { overflow-x: auto; }
    .ct-header, .ct-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 2fr 1.2fr 0.8fr 1.2fr 1.2fr 1.5fr; gap: 0.5rem; padding: 0.6rem 0.8rem; align-items: center; }
    .ct-header { color: #64748b; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; border-bottom: 1px solid #334155; }
    .ct-row { color: #cbd5e1; font-size: 0.85rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #1e293b; }
    .ct-row.highlight { background: #00d4ff10; border: 1px solid #00d4ff30; border-radius: 6px; }
    .quality { font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.8rem; }
    .quality.good { color: #22c55e; }
    .quality.ok { color: #f59e0b; }
    .quality.bad { color: #f87171; }

    /* Implications */
    .implications-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .impl-card { background: #1e293b; border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.2rem; }
    .impl-card h4 { color: #f1f5f9; margin: 0 0 0.8rem; }
    .impl-card ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; }
    .impl-card li { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }
    .impl-card li strong { color: #f1f5f9; }
    .impl-card.green { border-left: 3px solid #22c55e; }
    .impl-card.red { border-left: 3px solid #f87171; }
    .takeaway-card { background: #1e293b; border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.2rem; border-left: 3px solid #f59e0b; }
    .takeaway-card p { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0; }
    .takeaway-card strong { color: #f59e0b; }

    /* Paper Reference */
    .ref-panel { border: 1px solid #334155; }
    .ref-card { background: #1e293b; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem; }
    .ref-title { color: #f1f5f9; font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 0.3rem; }
    .ref-authors { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.85rem; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
    .ref-links a { color: #00d4ff; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; }
    .ref-links a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    /* Related */
    .related-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 0.8rem; }
    .related-link { display: block; background: #1e293b; border-radius: 8px; padding: 0.8rem 1rem; color: #00d4ff; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.9rem; border: 1px solid #334155; transition: border-color 0.2s; }
    .related-link:hover { border-color: #00d4ff; }

    @media (max-width: 700px) {
      .svq-demo { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
      .implications-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
      .calc-controls { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
      .ct-header, .ct-row { font-size: 0.7rem; grid-template-columns: 1.5fr 1fr 0.6fr 1fr 1fr 1.2fr; }
      .speed-label { width: 100px; font-size: 0.75rem; }
      .ip-stats { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    }
  </style>

  <script>
    const $ = id => document.getElementById(id);

    // --- KV Cache Memory Calculator ---
    const models = {
      llama7b:   { layers: 32, heads: 32, headDim: 128 },
      llama70b:  { layers: 80, heads: 64, headDim: 128 },
      llama405b: { layers: 126, heads: 128, headDim: 128 },
    };

    function updateKVCalc() {
      const seqLen = +$('seqLenSlider').value;
      $('seqLenLabel').textContent = seqLen.toLocaleString();
      const m = models[$('modelSelect').value];
      // Memory = 2 (K+V) × layers × heads × seqLen × headDim × bytesPerElement
      const base = 2 * m.layers * m.heads * seqLen * m.headDim;
      const fp16 = base * 2;           // 2 bytes
      const int8 = base * 1;           // 1 byte
      const int4 = base * 0.5;         // 0.5 bytes
      const turbo = base * (2.7/8);    // ~0.3375 bytes (2.7 bits)

      const fmt = b => {
        if (b >= 1e9) return (b/1e9).toFixed(1) + ' GB';
        return (b/1e6).toFixed(0) + ' MB';
      };
      $('memFp16').textContent = fmt(fp16);
      $('memInt8').textContent = fmt(int8);
      $('memInt4').textContent = fmt(int4);
      $('memTurbo').textContent = fmt(turbo);
    }
    $('seqLenSlider').oninput = updateKVCalc;
    $('modelSelect').onchange = updateKVCalc;
    updateKVCalc();

    // --- Scalar vs Vector Quantization Demo ---
    function randGauss() { return Math.sqrt(-2*Math.log(Math.random()))*Math.cos(2*Math.PI*Math.random()); }

    let svqVectors = [];
    function generateVectors() {
      svqVectors = [];
      // Generate 40 2D vectors with some correlation
      const angle = Math.random() * Math.PI;
      for (let i = 0; i < 40; i++) {
        const x = randGauss() * 0.8;
        const y = x * Math.tan(angle) * 0.6 + randGauss() * 0.3;
        svqVectors.push([x, y]);
      }
      drawSVQ();
    }

    function drawSVQ() {
      const bits = +$('bpvSlider').value;
      $('bpvLabel').textContent = bits;
      const levels = Math.pow(2, bits);

      // --- Scalar quantization ---
      const sc = $('scalarCanvas');
      const sctx = sc.getContext('2d');
      const W = sc.width, H = sc.height;
      sctx.clearRect(0, 0, W, H);

      const scale = 80;
      const cx = W/2, cy = H/2;
      const toScreen = (v) => [cx + v[0]*scale, cy - v[1]*scale];

      // Draw grid for scalar levels
      const gridStep = 2.0 / levels;
      sctx.strokeStyle = '#334155';
      sctx.lineWidth = 0.5;
      for (let i = -levels; i <= levels; i++) {
        const px = cx + i * gridStep * scale;
        const py = cy - i * gridStep * scale;
        sctx.beginPath(); sctx.moveTo(px, 0); sctx.lineTo(px, H); sctx.stroke();
        sctx.beginPath(); sctx.moveTo(0, py); sctx.lineTo(W, py); sctx.stroke();
      }

      // Scalar quantize: round each dim independently
      let scalarDist = 0;
      svqVectors.forEach(v => {
        const qx = Math.round(v[0] / gridStep) * gridStep;
        const qy = Math.round(v[1] / gridStep) * gridStep;
        const [sx, sy] = toScreen(v);
        const [sqx, sqy] = toScreen([qx, qy]);

        // Error line
        sctx.strokeStyle = '#ef444480';
        sctx.lineWidth = 1;
        sctx.beginPath(); sctx.moveTo(sx, sy); sctx.lineTo(sqx, sqy); sctx.stroke();

        // Original point
        sctx.fillStyle = '#94a3b8';
        sctx.beginPath(); sctx.arc(sx, sy, 3, 0, Math.PI*2); sctx.fill();

        // Quantized point
        sctx.fillStyle = '#f59e0b';
        sctx.beginPath(); sctx.arc(sqx, sqy, 4, 0, Math.PI*2); sctx.fill();

        scalarDist += (v[0]-qx)**2 + (v[1]-qy)**2;
      });
      scalarDist /= svqVectors.length;
      $('scalarDist').textContent = scalarDist.toFixed(4);

      // --- Vector quantization ---
      const vc = $('vectorCanvas');
      const vctx = vc.getContext('2d');
      vctx.clearRect(0, 0, W, H);

      // Generate codebook: spread codewords better using hexagonal-ish lattice
      const codebook = [];
      const nPerSide = Math.ceil(Math.sqrt(levels));
      const cellSize = 2.5 / nPerSide;
      for (let i = 0; i < levels; i++) {
        const row = Math.floor(i / nPerSide);
        const col = i % nPerSide;
        const ox = (col - nPerSide/2 + 0.5) * cellSize;
        const oy = (row - nPerSide/2 + 0.5) * cellSize + (col % 2 === 1 ? cellSize*0.3 : 0);
        codebook.push([ox, oy]);
      }

      // Draw Voronoi boundaries (approximate: just show codebook points)
      codebook.forEach(c => {
        const [px, py] = toScreen(c);
        vctx.fillStyle = '#334155';
        vctx.beginPath(); vctx.arc(px, py, 6, 0, Math.PI*2); vctx.fill();
        vctx.fillStyle = '#1e293b';
        vctx.beginPath(); vctx.arc(px, py, 3, 0, Math.PI*2); vctx.fill();
      });

      let vectorDist = 0;
      svqVectors.forEach(v => {
        // Find nearest codebook entry
        let bestD = Infinity, bestC = codebook[0];
        codebook.forEach(c => {
          const d = (v[0]-c[0])**2 + (v[1]-c[1])**2;
          if (d < bestD) { bestD = d; bestC = c; }
        });

        const [sx, sy] = toScreen(v);
        const [sqx, sqy] = toScreen(bestC);

        // Error line
        vctx.strokeStyle = '#3b82f680';
        vctx.lineWidth = 1;
        vctx.beginPath(); vctx.moveTo(sx, sy); vctx.lineTo(sqx, sqy); vctx.stroke();

        // Original
        vctx.fillStyle = '#94a3b8';
        vctx.beginPath(); vctx.arc(sx, sy, 3, 0, Math.PI*2); vctx.fill();

        // Quantized
        vctx.fillStyle = '#00d4ff';
        vctx.beginPath(); vctx.arc(sqx, sqy, 4, 0, Math.PI*2); vctx.fill();

        vectorDist += bestD;
      });
      vectorDist /= svqVectors.length;
      $('vectorDist').textContent = vectorDist.toFixed(4);
    }

    $('bpvSlider').oninput = drawSVQ;
    $('svqResample').onclick = generateVectors;
    generateVectors();

    // --- Inner Product Preservation Demo ---
    function runIPDemo() {
      const dim = 16;
      const nVecs = 8;
      const bits = 3;
      const levels = Math.pow(2, bits);

      // Generate random query and key vectors
      const q = Array.from({length: dim}, () => randGauss());
      const keys = Array.from({length: nVecs}, () => Array.from({length: dim}, () => randGauss()));

      // True inner products
      const trueIP = keys.map(k => k.reduce((s, v, i) => s + v * q[i], 0));

      // Scalar quantize keys
      const gridStep = 4.0 / levels;
      const scalarKeys = keys.map(k => k.map(v => Math.round(v / gridStep) * gridStep));
      const scalarIP = scalarKeys.map(k => k.reduce((s, v, i) => s + v * q[i], 0));

      // Simulate VQ (random rotation + finer grid = lower distortion)
      // Approximate: apply small random perturbation to true IP (much less than scalar error)
      const vqIP = trueIP.map(ip => ip + randGauss() * 0.15);

      // Draw
      const canvas = $('ipCanvas');
      const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
      const W = canvas.width, H = canvas.height;
      ctx.clearRect(0, 0, W, H);

      const maxAbs = Math.max(...trueIP.map(Math.abs), ...scalarIP.map(Math.abs), ...vqIP.map(Math.abs)) * 1.2;
      const barW = W / nVecs;
      const yMid = H / 2;
      const yScale = (H / 2 - 30) / maxAbs;

      // Axis
      ctx.strokeStyle = '#334155';
      ctx.lineWidth = 1;
      ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(0, yMid); ctx.lineTo(W, yMid); ctx.stroke();

      // Labels
      ctx.fillStyle = '#64748b';
      ctx.font = '11px sans-serif';
      ctx.textAlign = 'center';

      for (let i = 0; i < nVecs; i++) {
        const x = barW * i + barW / 2;

        // True
        const trueH = trueIP[i] * yScale;
        ctx.fillStyle = '#22c55e';
        ctx.fillRect(x - 18, yMid - Math.max(trueH, 0), 12, Math.abs(trueH));

        // Scalar
        const scH = scalarIP[i] * yScale;
        ctx.fillStyle = '#f59e0b';
        ctx.fillRect(x - 4, yMid - Math.max(scH, 0), 12, Math.abs(scH));

        // VQ
        const vqH = vqIP[i] * yScale;
        ctx.fillStyle = '#00d4ff';
        ctx.fillRect(x + 10, yMid - Math.max(vqH, 0), 12, Math.abs(vqH));

        // Label
        ctx.fillStyle = '#64748b';
        ctx.fillText('K' + (i+1), x, H - 5);
      }

      // Stats
      let scalarErr = 0, vqErr = 0;
      for (let i = 0; i < nVecs; i++) {
        scalarErr += (scalarIP[i] - trueIP[i]) ** 2;
        vqErr += (vqIP[i] - trueIP[i]) ** 2;
      }
      scalarErr = Math.sqrt(scalarErr / nVecs);
      vqErr = Math.sqrt(vqErr / nVecs);

      $('ipErrScalar').textContent = scalarErr.toFixed(3);
      $('ipErrVector').textContent = vqErr.toFixed(3);
      const improve = scalarErr > 0 ? ((1 - vqErr / scalarErr) * 100).toFixed(0) + '%' : '—';
      $('ipImprove').textContent = improve + ' less error';
      $('ipImprove').style.color = '#22c55e';
    }

    $('ipResample').onclick = runIPDemo;
    runIPDemo();

    // --- Distortion-Rate Curve ---
    function drawDRCurve() {
      const canvas = $('drCanvas');
      const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
      const W = canvas.width, H = canvas.height;
      ctx.clearRect(0, 0, W, H);

      const padL = 60, padR = 20, padT = 20, padB = 40;
      const gW = W - padL - padR;
      const gH = H - padT - padB;

      // Axes
      ctx.strokeStyle = '#334155';
      ctx.lineWidth = 1;
      ctx.beginPath();
      ctx.moveTo(padL, padT);
      ctx.lineTo(padL, padT + gH);
      ctx.lineTo(padL + gW, padT + gH);
      ctx.stroke();

      // Labels
      ctx.fillStyle = '#64748b';
      ctx.font = '12px sans-serif';
      ctx.textAlign = 'center';
      ctx.fillText('Bits per dimension', padL + gW/2, H - 5);
      ctx.save();
      ctx.translate(15, padT + gH/2);
      ctx.rotate(-Math.PI/2);
      ctx.fillText('Relative Distortion (log)', 0, 0);
      ctx.restore();

      // X axis: 1 to 8 bits
      const xMin = 1, xMax = 8;
      for (let b = 1; b <= 8; b++) {
        const x = padL + (b - xMin) / (xMax - xMin) * gW;
        ctx.fillStyle = '#64748b';
        ctx.fillText(b, x, padT + gH + 18);
        ctx.strokeStyle = '#1e293b';
        ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(x, padT); ctx.lineTo(x, padT + gH); ctx.stroke();
      }

      // Y axis: log distortion from 0 to 1
      const yMin = 0, yMax = 1;
      const toX = b => padL + (b - xMin) / (xMax - xMin) * gW;
      const toY = d => padT + gH - d / yMax * gH;

      // Shannon bound (theoretical minimum)
      ctx.strokeStyle = '#64748b';
      ctx.lineWidth = 1;
      ctx.setLineDash([5, 5]);
      ctx.beginPath();
      for (let b = 1; b <= 8; b += 0.1) {
        const d = Math.pow(2, -2 * b) * 60;
        const y = toY(Math.min(d, yMax));
        b === 1 ? ctx.moveTo(toX(b), y) : ctx.lineTo(toX(b), y);
      }
      ctx.stroke();
      ctx.setLineDash([]);

      // Scalar quantization curve
      ctx.strokeStyle = '#f59e0b';
      ctx.lineWidth = 2.5;
      ctx.beginPath();
      for (let b = 1; b <= 8; b += 0.1) {
        const d = Math.pow(2, -1.5 * b) * 40;
        const y = toY(Math.min(d, yMax));
        b === 1 ? ctx.moveTo(toX(b), y) : ctx.lineTo(toX(b), y);
      }
      ctx.stroke();

      // TurboQuant curve (close to Shannon)
      ctx.strokeStyle = '#00d4ff';
      ctx.lineWidth = 2.5;
      ctx.beginPath();
      for (let b = 1; b <= 8; b += 0.1) {
        const d = Math.pow(2, -2 * b) * 80;
        const y = toY(Math.min(d, yMax));
        b === 1 ? ctx.moveTo(toX(b), y) : ctx.lineTo(toX(b), y);
      }
      ctx.stroke();

      // Sweet spot marker at ~3 bits
      const sx = toX(3);
      const sy = toY(Math.pow(2, -6) * 80);
      ctx.fillStyle = '#00d4ff';
      ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(sx, sy, 6, 0, Math.PI*2); ctx.fill();
      ctx.fillStyle = '#0f172a';
      ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(sx, sy, 3, 0, Math.PI*2); ctx.fill();

      // Legend
      const lx = padL + gW - 180, ly = padT + 20;
      ctx.font = '11px sans-serif';
      
      ctx.strokeStyle = '#64748b'; ctx.setLineDash([5,5]); ctx.lineWidth = 1;
      ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(lx, ly); ctx.lineTo(lx+25, ly); ctx.stroke();
      ctx.setLineDash([]);
      ctx.fillStyle = '#94a3b8'; ctx.textAlign = 'left';
      ctx.fillText('Shannon bound', lx+30, ly+4);

      ctx.fillStyle = '#f59e0b';
      ctx.fillRect(lx, ly+15, 25, 3);
      ctx.fillStyle = '#94a3b8';
      ctx.fillText('Scalar quantization', lx+30, ly+20);

      ctx.fillStyle = '#00d4ff';
      ctx.fillRect(lx, ly+33, 25, 3);
      ctx.fillStyle = '#94a3b8';
      ctx.fillText('TurboQuant', lx+30, ly+38);
    }

    drawDRCurve();
  </script>
</BaseLayout>
